Interface StringList

  • All Superinterfaces:
    Iterable<String>
    All Known Implementing Classes:
    AbstractStringList, ArrayStringList, LinkedStringList

    public interface StringList
extends Iterable<String>
    This interface represents an ordered collection (also known as a sequence) of strings. The user of this interface has precise control over where in the list each element is inserted. The user can access elements by their integer index (position in the list), and search for elements in the list.

    All StringList implementations should prohibit null elements and empty strings (i.e., strings of length zero) within the lists themselves. This restriction does not apply to the list's internal storage mechanism as that is obscured from the end user. Attempting to add a prohibited element to a list should throw an unchecked exception, typically NullPointerException or IllegalArgumentException. In general, implementors should throw the exceptions described by each method's documentation under the conditions described therein.

    Required Constructors

    All classes that implement this interface must support the following constructors, where ClassName is the name of the implementing class:
    • Constructors and Description
      public ClassName()
      The implementing class must explicitly define a default constructor. The initial size of a list object constructed using this constructor is zero, regardless of the list's underlying storage.
      public ClassName(StringList other)
      The implementing class must explicitly define a copy constructor. It should take exactly one parameter of the interface type StringList. The list object that is constructed using this constructor should be a deep copy of the list referred to by the constructor's parameter (i.e., after the new list is constructed, they contain the same elements in the same order, and changes to one list do not impact the other). Therefore, the initial size and elements of the new list object will be the same as the other list. While the newly constructed list is a deep copy of the other list, the individual elements do not need to be deep copies. To be clear, the other list can be an object of any implementation of the StringList interface. No other assumptions about the type of the object should be made. This constructor should throw a NullPointerException if the specified list is null.

    Examples

    Listed below are some code examples. The classes SomeStringList, SomeOtherStringList, and YetAnotherStringList are all assumed to correctly implement the StringList interface. 
     StringList list = new SomeStringList();
 System.out.println(list.size());              // 0
 list.add("a");
 list.add("b");
 list.add("c");
 System.out.println(list.makeString(", "));    // a, b, c

 StringList other = new SomeOtherStringOther();
 other.add("d");
 other.add(0, "e");
 other.add(0, "f");
 System.out.println(other.size());             // 3
 System.out.println(other.makeString(", "));   // f, e, d

 StringList another = new YetAnotherStringList(list);
 System.out.println(another.size());           // 3
 System.out.println(another.makeString(", ")); // a, b, c
 another.add(0, other);
 System.out.println(another.size());           // 6
 System.out.println(another.makeString(", ")); // f, e, d, a, b, c
    The above examples are not exhaustive, however, they do show how different implementations of this interface can interact with each other towards the creation and modification of lists.

    • Method Detail

      • size

        int size()
        Returns the number of elements in this list. If this list contains more than Integer.MAX_VALUE elements, then this method returns Integer.MAX_VALUE.

        Note: The size of this list may be different from the size of its internal storage. This can happen, for example, if the list is backed by an array, and the list internally reserved extra space for future and/or recently removed elements.

        Hint: If at all possible, try to avoid recalculating the list size every time this method is called. Instead, using and maintaining an instance variable might make this method a one-liner.

        Returns:
        the number of elements in this list

      • isEmpty

        boolean isEmpty()
        Returns true if this list contains no elements.

        Note: The emptiness of this list has nothing to do with the size or contents of its internal storage. Formally, a list is empty if, and only if, its list size is zero.

        Hint: You may be able to use the return value of another StringList method to easily implement this method without duplicating code. We are not going to repeat this statement throughout the documentation (it applies in many places), because making this observation is part of the Suggested Checklist section in the project description.

        Returns:
        true if this list contains no elements

      • toArray

        String[] toArray()
        Returns a new array containing all of the strings in this list in proper sequence (from first to last element). The new array will be the same size as this list. The returned array will be "safe" in that no references to it are maintained by this list. In other words, this method must allocate a new array even if this list is backed by an array. The caller is thus free to modify the returned array.
        Returns:
        an array containing all of the strings in this list in proper sequence

      • makeString

        default String makeString()
        Returns a string representation of this list with all of strings directly concatenated in order. The default implementation is to return makeString(""). Here is an example, assuming list refers to an empty StringList: 
         list.add("a");
 list.add("b");
 list.add("c");
 String result = list.makeString();
 System.out.println(result);
        The output would be: 
         abc

        Note: This method does not need to be overridden / implemented in the implementing class so long as makeString(String) is implemented correctly.

        Returns:
        the concatenation of all strings in this list

      • makeString

        default String makeString(String start,
                          String sep,
                          String end)
        Returns a string representation of this list that begins with start and ends with end, with every string in the sequence separated by sep. The default implementation relies on a correctly implemented makeString(String) method. Here is an example, assuming list refers to an empty StringList: 
         list.add("a");
 list.add("b");
 list.add("c");
 String result = list.makeString("~", "!", "#");
 System.out.println(result);
        The output would be: 
         ~a!b!c#

        Note: This method does not need to be overridden / implemented in the implementing class so long as makeString(String) is implemented correctly.

        Parameters:
        start - specified starting string
        sep - the specified separator string
        end - the specified ending string
        Returns:
        a string representation of this list that begins with start and ends with end, with every string in the sequence separated by sep

      • splice

        StringList splice(int fromIndex,
                  int toIndex)
        Builds and returns a new StringList that contains the strings from this list between the specified fromIndex, inclusive, and toIndex, exclusive. If fromIndex and toIndex are in bounds and equal, then the returned list is empty. The resulting object is expected to be the same implementation as the calling object.
        Parameters:
        fromIndex - low endpoint (inclusive) of the splice
        toIndex - high endpoint (exclusive) of the splice
        Returns:
        a new StringList with the strings from this list from the specified range
        Throws:
        IndexOutOfBoundsException - for an illegal endpoint index value (fromIndex < 0 || toIndex > size || fromIndex > toIndex)

      • iterator

        default Iterator<String> iterator()
        Returns a new iterator over the strings in this list in proper sequence. The default implementation throws a UnsupportedOperationException. Students who wish to earn extra credit may properly override this method in the implementing class to return a new object of a minimal, correct Iterator implementation. Doing so will enable objects of their StringList implementation to be the targets of "for-each loop" statements.

        For this extra credit, student's are not required to support the Iterator.remove() operation in the iterator. However, the Iterator.next() and Iterator.hasNext() operations are required.

        Failure Mechanics: Users of this method should assume that an iterator object produced by this method is invalidated if the list is modified. That is, if the list is modified after an iterator object is created, then that iterator object should no longer be used. Implementors of this method are not expected to explicitly handle situations resulting from concurrent modification of the list.

        Here is an example, assuming list refers to an empty StringList: 

         list.add("aa");
 list.add("bb");
 list.add("cc");
 Iterator<String> it = list.iterator();
 while (it.hasNext()) {
     String elem = it.next();
     System.out.printf("%s ", elem);
 } // while
 System.out.println();
        The output would be: 
         aa bb cc

        Properly implementing this method also allows for a list object to be the target of a "for-each" loop. Here is an example, assuming list refers to an empty StringList: 

         list.add("a");
 list.add("smooth");
 list.add("criminal");
 for (String elem : list) {
     System.out.printf("%s ", elem);
 } // for
 System.out.println();
        The output would be: 
         a smooth criminal

        Hint: In order to return a reference to an Iterator<String that behaves correctly, you should create a new class that implements that interface. Don't worry too much about the angle brackets (we'll cover those late); just make sure that you have implements Iterator<String> in your class signature. How does an object of that class get access to this list? You might pass a StringList reference to it via one of its constructors, then use that here when you make the object. If you stick to the interface and only use interface methods, then you may be able to get away with only writing one iterator class that works with both of your StringList implementations.

        Specified by:
        iterator in interface Iterable<String>
        Returns:
        an iterator over the strings in this list in proper sequence.
        Throws:
        UnsupportedOperationException - if the iterator operation is not supported by this list
        See Also:
        The Iterator Interface, Oracle: The Java For-Each Loop
